		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Mathematical notation</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="/wiki/Table_of_mathematical_symbols" title="Table of mathematical symbols">Table of mathematical symbols</a></div>
<p>A <b>mathematical notation</b> is a system of <a href="/wiki/Symbolic" title="Symbolic" class="mw-redirect">symbolic</a> representations of mathematical objects and ideas. Mathematical notations are used in <a href="/wiki/Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Physical_sciences" title="Physical sciences" class="mw-redirect">physical sciences</a>, <a href="/wiki/Engineering" title="Engineering">engineering</a> and <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">economics</a>. Mathematical notations include relatively simple symbolic representations, such as numbers <a href="/wiki/1_(number)" title="1 (number)">1</a> and <a href="/wiki/2_(number)" title="2 (number)">2</a>, <a href="/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title="Function (mathematics)">function</a> symbols <a href="/wiki/Sine" title="Sine" class="mw-redirect">sin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Addition" title="Addition">+</a>; conceptual symbols, such as <a href="/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title="Limit (mathematics)">lim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Derivative" title="Derivative"><i>dy/dx</i></a>, <a href="/wiki/Equation" title="Equation">equations</a> and <a href="/wiki/Variable" title="Variable">variables</a>; and complex diagramatic notations such as <a href="/wiki/Penrose_graphical_notation" title="Penrose graphical notation">Penrose graphical notation</a> and <a href="/wiki/Coxeter-Dynkin_diagram" title="Coxeter-Dynkin diagram">Coxeter-Dynkin diagrams</a>.</p>
